iap: {
title: 'IAP Lookup',
sub: 'Query App Store app info, pricing, and in-app purchase markers. Individual apps can reveal IAP items and prices.',
intro: {
heading: 'About IAP Lookup',
p1: 'In-App Purchases (IAP) are a critical part of the App Store economy. Many apps appear free but hide core functionality behind paywalls. Before downloading, it pays to check: Does this app have IAP? If so, what are they and how much do they cost? Our IAP Lookup tool answers these questions before you install.',
p2: 'Search by app name, Bundle ID, or App Store Track ID. The tool queries the iTunes Search API to fetch app metadata — price, universal support (iPhone + iPad), age rating, and description — then automatically visits the actual App Store product page via a proxy to detect in-app purchase markers and extract IAP item names and prices when publicly available.',
p3: 'For apps with visible IAP listings, you will see a detailed breakdown of each purchase item and its price. The tool distinguishes between confirmed IAP (detected on the store page), pending (not yet verified), and apps that appear to lack IAP. You can also switch between regional App Stores (US, China, Japan, etc.) to compare IAP availability across markets.',
p4: 'Tips: Use Bundle ID search for precision — each app has a unique reverse-domain identifier like "com.developer.appname". If IAP items are not visible, try switching to the US App Store, which typically has the most complete public listing. The "Fill Bundle ID" button helps you chain searches: after finding an app, click it to search by its exact bundle ID for more detailed results.',
},
howItWorks: {
heading: 'How It Works',
p1: 'The Price Compare tool queries the iTunes Search API and App Store lookup endpoints to fetch real-time pricing data for any app across multiple regional App Stores simultaneously. When you enter an app name, Bundle ID, or App Store URL, the tool resolves the app\u2019s unique identifier and queries each supported region\u2019s storefront.',
p2: 'Apple sets prices per region using a tier system. Each tier maps to a local currency price point. The tool displays these prices side-by-side in a comparison table, highlighting the cheapest and most expensive regions. Currency conversion uses near-real-time exchange rates so you can see approximate equivalent costs.',
p3: 'The tool also surfaces metadata: app category, age rating, whether the app includes IAPs, and developer name. This additional context helps you evaluate whether a lower price in another region actually represents a genuine saving — some regional versions may differ in features, language support, or available IAPs.',
},
troubleshooting: {
heading: 'Common Issues',
items: [
'App not found: try using the Apple ID (numeric) or Bundle ID instead of the app name. Some apps are not available in all regions, so the tool may find them in some regions but not others.',
'Price shows as N/A: this usually means the app is either free, not listed in that region, or removed from sale. Check the App Store directly for that region to confirm.',
'Incorrect currency display: exchange rates update periodically. For exact regional pricing, cross-reference with the App Store in that region.',
'Results take a long time: querying multiple regions requires multiple API calls. If the app has many regional versions, try fewer regions or use a specific Bundle ID.',
],
},
placeholder: 'Enter app name / Bundle ID / Track ID / App Store link',
howItWorks: {
heading: 'How It Works',
p1: 'The IAP Lookup tool queries the App Store\u2019s product metadata endpoint to retrieve the complete list of in-app purchases available for a given app. By providing a Bundle ID (the unique reverse-domain identifier like com.developer.appname), the tool fetches the app\u2019s IAP catalog including item names, descriptions, price tiers, and types.',
p2: 'Apple classifies IAPs into four types: Consumable (one-time use, like game currency), Non-Consumable (permanent unlock, like ad removal), Auto-Renewable Subscription (recurring billing), and Non-Renewing Subscription (fixed-term access). The tool labels each IAP with its type so you can distinguish between one-time purchases and recurring commitments before downloading the app.',
p3: 'The tool also shows whether the app supports Family Sharing for its IAPs — indicated by a special flag in Apple\u2019s metadata. IAPs with Family Sharing enabled can be shared across up to six family members without additional purchase. This is particularly valuable for evaluating the true cost of apps with paid content.',
},
troubleshooting: {
heading: 'Common Issues',
items: [
'Bundle ID not found: verify the exact Bundle ID. You can find it in the app\u2019s App Store URL (after /id... use the numeric ID in a lookup tool) or by searching for the app on the Price Compare page.',
'IAP list shows fewer items than expected: some IAPs are region-specific and only appear when querying from certain App Store regions. The tool queries the US store by default.',
'Subscription pricing varies: auto-renewable subscription prices displayed are introductory or standard tier prices. Actual pricing may differ based on region, promotional offers, or Family Sharing status.',
'IAP type unknown: some legacy IAPs use older schemas that do not clearly indicate type. In these cases, check the App Store listing directly for more detail.',
],
},
